passages.text: Sequential revenue/GPM growth in 2Q25, but earnings missed due to elevated R&D

Transsion reported 2Q25 net profit of Rmb723mn, a \(41\%\) yoy decline and \(40\%\) below JPMc, despite in- line revenue and GPM, which we primarily attribute to elevated R&D spending (up \(32\%\) yoy vs a \(6\%\) yoy revenue decline). We expect sequential revenue and GPM growth in 2H25, driven by the introduction of new models featuring higher ASP and GPM leading to \(4\%\) yoy net profit growth. Looking to 2026/27, we expect 1) LSD yoy growth for both shipments and ASP, 2) stabilizing GPM with mixed impact from product upgrades and price pressure amid competition, 3) disciplined opex, though still above our previous expectation, and 4) increasing JV income with independent application monetization. We estimate \(19\% /14\%\) yoy earnings growth for 2026/27, which we think is insufficient to support a valuation re- rate. We stay Neutral on Transsion with a new Jun- 26 PT of Rmb78.

- 2Q25 earnings missed due to elevated R&D. Transsion achieved in- line revenue of Rmb16.1bn (6% yoy decline, 24% qoq growth) and GPM of \(20.8\%\) (up 1.5ppt qoq) in 2Q25. We attribute the sequential growth to the introduction of new models featuring higher ASP and GPM (with memory price increase pressure partially considered), which should drive HoH shipment and revenue growth in 2H25. However, earnings fell by \(41\%\) yoy and were \(40\%\) below our estimate. This was primarily due to elevated R&D spending (mainly for AI feature development and appearance upgrades) which we think will enhance Transsion's competency and support share gains, but may also hurt earnings to some extent, especially with margin pressure from memory cost increase (this year) and persisting competition.

- Lower earnings forecasts. We cut 2025-27 earnings forecast by \(15 - 19\%\) to reflect elevated R&D and macro headwinds. We now project net profit of Rmb4.0bn for 2025 and expect \(19\% /14\%\) yoy growth in 2026/27, driven by 1) LSD growth for both shipments and ASP, 2) stabilizing GPM (as the company now cares about profitability more than volume growth), 3) disciplined opex on a yoy basis (but still above our previous assumptions), and 4) increasing JV income from independent application monetization.

- Neutral. Transsion's share price has fallen by \(10\%\) and underperformed the SW electronics index by 49ppt YTD. Our current estimates are \(\sim 30\%\) below Wind consensus but we think investors now have fair expectations about this, given the stock's underperformance against improving sentiment. We rolled over our PT to June-26 at Rmb78 (from Dec-25 Rmb86), based on an unchanged \(17x\) 1yr forward PE. We stay Neutral on Transsion.

Overall, we estimate a \(27.5\%\) yoy earnings decline for 2025 and growth of \(19\% /14\%\) yoy in 2026/27. Stay Neutral.
